{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346978/1938010501/0037.xml":{"full_text":"The Weather\nGenerally Fair, Cold\nTonight, Thursday\nFull Weather Report Page 3\nmtfttrai\nHome Edition\nLate Sport News\n1:15 Stock Prices\nESTABLISHED 1881\nVOL. LVI, NO. 3\nWATERBURY, CONNECTICUT, WEDNESDAY, JANUARY 5, 1938\nEIGHTEEN PAGES PRICE THREE CENTS\nJUSTICE GEORGE SUTHERLAND RETIRES\nCity Employes Fail to Get Paid\nController Claims\nHe Was Too Busy\nWhen Questioned\nMayor Hayes, City Clerk Fitzmaurice Spent Entire\nMorning Signing Checks\u2014Employes of City\nWaited in Vain to Get Their Money\nThousands of city employes waited in vain for their\npay today, their first checks since the week before Christ\nmas. Mayor Frank Hayes and City Clerk John P. Fitz\nmaurice had spent the entire morning signing the checks.\nBut, for the first time in eight years, including many times\nwhen there was a question of whether the money would\nbe available at the height of the depression, the checks\nwere held up. City Controller Sherwood L. Rowland had\ntne cnecKs in ms oriice, awaiting\nhie signature.\nThe paymaster reported that he\nwas unable to get them until they\nwere countersigned by the new Re\npublican controller.\nAll Out In Cold\nMeanwhile, employes of the Police\nDepartment, usually paid at 1\no'clock, of the Fire Department,\nStreet Department, engineering\nsewer, water, parks, non-teaching\nemployes of the schools, waited and\nwondered when the \u2018'ghost would\nwalk.\"\nController Too Busy\nFinally, just after 1 o\u2019clock, the\ncity controller was reached by tele\nphone.\n\"Any statements to make on the\n(Continued on Page 4)\nBROTHERS SEEK\nVINDICATION\nStanley, George Beckett of\nDanbury Claim Warrant\nWas Unsigned\nAn unsigned warrant, upon which\ntwo brothers, Stanley and George\nBeckett of West Main street, this\ncity were allegedly arrested and\nfined $25 and costs in city court\nlast September, was the basis of\nclaim in the court of common pleas\ntoday, that the brothers should be\nvindicated of charges. The case\nmay go to the supreme court.\nAttorney Joseph C. Guilfoile, their\ncounsel made the claim, which was\nargued against by Pros. Attorney\nWilliam J. Larkin, with reservation\nof decision being made by Judge\nEdward J. Finn. Judge Finn will\nrule on the motion before hearing\nthe actual evetiince of the case,\nwhich has been assigned for Jan\nuary 18.\nFight With Negro\nThe men. now temporary residents\nof Danbury, were charged with as\nsault and breach of the peace, fol\nlowing an altercation with a negro\nin a West End Grill, August 22.\nThey pleaded not guilty, and when\nfined, appealed to the court of\ncommon pleas.\nAlthough not officially ruling on\nthe motion, Judge Finn said that he\nbelieved the question of jurisdiction,\nin view of the allegedly unsigned\nwarrant, would have to be decided\nGuilfoile contended that as the\nwarrant for arrest was not signed\nby any prosecutor, there was not\nat any time any actual charges\nagainst his clients.\nYOUTH HELD FOR\nWIDOW MURDER\nLouisville, Ky., Jan. 5.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nWendell P. Bowers, 19, who con\nfessed that he killed a Philadelphia\nwidow while looting her home last\nDec. 13, pleaded guilty before U. S.\nCommissioner Ray H. Kirchborser\ntoday to a charge of unlawful flight\nto a\\\u20acid prosecution and was re\nturned to Jefferson county jail in\ndefault of $25,000 bond.\nAuthorities said he would be re\nturned to Pennsylvania later today.\nThe youth appeared calm at his\narraignment. He wore a grey jacket.\nOn his left arm were tatooer the\ninitials \"W. B.\u201d\nBowers had been held here for\ntwo weeks on a vagrancy charge\nand was about to be released when\nFederal Bureau of Investigation of\nficlals, in making a routine finger\nprint check, discovered the prints\ntallied with those of the slayer of\nMrs. Wilma C. Carpenter.\nSHIPPERS READY\n9 TO OPPOSE UNION\nSeattle, Wash., Jan. 6\u2014(UP)\u2014\nBhippers prepared to break rela\ntions with the Longshoremen's\nUnion at noon today because of a\ndispute over the throwing of cargoes\nfrom one boat to another in the har\nbor, without landing it at the docks\nfor longshoremen to handle.\nThe break In relations was ex\npected to tie up shipping here im\nmediately as similar breaks have\ndone in the past. Union leaders said\nthe trouble might easily develop into\nj a coastwise tie-up. Shippers did not\nbelieve It would,\nA\nYOUTH IS SHOT\nDEADBY POLICE\nProvidence Lad Trying to\nEscape in Stolen Car\nWhen Killed\nDarien, Conn., Jan. 5.\u2014(UP).\u2014An\n18-year-old Providence, R. I., youth\nwas killed by police today as he and\na companion led a 70-miles-an-hour\nchase through three towns in a\nstolen car.\nThe victim was Harry Smith, 186\nCrary street. His companion, held on j\na charge of possessing a stolen auto\nmobile, was Angelo Lalkas, 20, of 189\nCrary street. According to Police\ni Capt. John McCarthy the car\nstopped at a Norwalk filling station\nI owned by Samuel Hall, where the\nI youths demanded gas and then sped\naway without paying.\nTrail Picked Up\nThey avoided Stamford authori\nties but at Darien their trail was\npicked up by two radio cars. Dur-\ning the chase the pursued machine\nskidded into a railroad abutment, j\nmade a complete turn in the road\nand faced the oncoming police car.\nOfficer William Foreit alighted from\nhis machine with gun drawn. He\nsaid Smith pointed a revolver at\nhim through a window of the dam\naged car and he fired through the\ndoor. The bullet pierced the youth\u2019s\ni chest, killing Him almost instantly.\nLakkas, cowering in the front seat\ni beside the body of his companion,\nwas manacled and taken to head\nquarters. He said he was driving the\nj car and refused to heed police com\nI mands to halt because he feared\nSmith would kill him.\nStolen Last Night\nThe machine in which they were\nriding was reported by William Hol\nj loway, West Warwick, R. I., as hav\ning been stolen from a Providence\nI parking lot last night. Lalkas said\nhe and Smith, driving to New York,\nbroke into a New Haven gasoline\nstation late last night and stole a\nflashlight. When Hall notified police\nhe said he counted six young men\nin the machine. Lalkas steadfastly\nmaintained he and Smith were the\nsole occupants.\nLate News\nBulletins\nMISSIONARY DIES\nBoston, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014\nMiss Mary G. Webb, 83, re\ntired missionary, is dead at\nBeirut, Syria, according to\nword received here by the\nAmerican Board for For\neign Missions. A native of\nEsopus, N. Y., Miss Webb\nserved 38 years in Turkey\nbefore her retirement in\n1928.\nEVERYBODY AIDS\nWashington, Jan. 5\u2014\n(UP)\u2014If every man, wom\nan and child in the United\nStates were asked to con\ntribute equally to liquidate\nthe $38,528,000,000 public\ndebt estimated for the fiscal\nyear 1939, each would have\nto pay approximately $273.\nFOURTH SON\nHollywood, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\n\u2014A soiv was born today to\nMrs. Dixie Lee Crosby, wife\nof Bing Crosby, radio\ncrooner. It was Crosby\u2019s\nfourth son. The 6 pound,\n5 ounce baby was born in\nCedars of Lebanon hospital.\nThe other Crosby children\nare Gary Evans Crosby, 4,\nand Philip and Dennis, 2\nyear-old twins.\nROWLAND STILL\nSEARCHING FOR\nLOST RECORDS\nTwo Warrant Books in His\nOffice Have Strangely\nWandered Away\nEVERYBODY SEEMS TOO\nBUSY TO EXPLAIN\nEx=Controller Leary Says\nEverything Was 0. K.\nWhen He Left Office\nMystery of the \u201cmissing\npapers\u201d created grotesque\nshadows today in that corner\nof City Hall where Controller\nSherwood L. Rowland held\ncouncil with Republican\nleaders, between times order\ning his transient staff to pre\npare the city payroll checks.\n\u201cToo busy. Tied up. Mr. Row\nland cannot be reached.\u201d\nSuch was the answer to\nattempts to find explanation of what\nthe controller meant when he an\nnounced by special dispen\nsation of the morning paper that\n\"important records\u201d are missing.\n\"Most important records,\u201d sec\nonded James F. Purcell, Democratic\noppointee, who, report has it. is now\nthe spearhead of a political move\n(Continued on Page 4)\nTOM HEFLIN IS\nBADLY BEATEN\nLister Hill, New Dealer,\nDefeated Him By Almost\nTwo to One\nBirmingham. Ala., Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014\nJ. Thomas Heflin\u2019s attempted politi- j\ncal \u201ccome-back\u201d was lost today in\na flood of votes for Rep. Lester Hill,\nstaunch New Dealer, to succeed Su\npreme Court Justice Hugo L. Black\nin the U. S. senate. Returns com\nplete save for scattered rural pre\ncincts late last night from a three\nman Democratic primary showed:\nHill, 74,872; Heflin, 39,263; Charles\nWilliams, \"dirt\u201d farmer, 4,328.\nMay Be Appointed\nGovernor Bibb Graves is expected\nto appoint him to the senate, thus\navoiding an election, when the offi\ncial tabulation of the primary is\ncompleted. Mrs. Dixie Graves, his\nwife, who has been serving in Black's\nseat temporarily, will resign.\nThe primary had been considered\nby some observers as a test of New\nDeal sentiment in the deep south.\nHill, an ardent supporter of the\nRoosevelt administration and one of\nthe few southerners who endorsed\nthe wages and hours bill in the house\nof representatives, ran on a \"strictly\n100 per cent New Deal\u201d platform.\nHeflin, whose colorful senate ca\nreer ended when Alabamans voted\nhim out because he bolted the Dem\nocratic national ticket in the 1928\ncampaign, had promised to \"support\nRoosevelt when I think it is right.\u201d\nMRS. RUBENS IS\nMRS. ROBINSON\nMoscow, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014A picture\nof Mrs. Adolph Arnold Rubens of\nNew York, which the State Depart\nment at Washington radioed to Mos\ncow, was identified today by Ameri\ncans as \u2018\u2018Mrs. Donald L. Robinson,\"\nwho is held by the Soviet on espio\nnage charges.\nAmericans who saw Mrs. Robinson\nthe day before she \u201cdisappeared\u201d\nfrom the National Hotel examined\nthe photograph of Mrs. Rubens and\nthat of her husband. They were un\nable to identify the photograph of\nRubens.\nThe \u201cRobinson\u201d couple entered\nRussia early in December on fradu\nlent American passports. Robinson\n\u201cdisappeared\u201d about a week before\nhis wife did. Soviet officials admitted\nlater that both were under arrest.\nDOUGLAS WILL BE.\nGUEST SPEAKER\nNew Haven, Conn., Jan. 5.\u2014(UP)\n\u2014William O. Douglas, chairman of\nthe securities and exchange commis\nsion, will be guest speaker at the\nDemocratic Jackson Day dinner here\nSaturday night.\nMore than 400 party members, pay\ning $25 a plate, were expected to be\npresent. The list of speakers was ex\npected to include Oov. Wilbur L.\nCross, U. S. Senators Francis T.\nMaloney and Augustine Lonergan.\nand National Committeeman David\nE. FitzGerald,\nConfess Slaying Bus Driver In Holdup\n__ _\n(Acme Telephoto)\nMiss Genevieve Owens of 625 East Ferry street, Newark, (left), and\nMrs. Ethel Strouse Sohl, of the same address, who today confessed the\nholdup slaying of William Barhorst, bus driver, in Belleville, N. J., two\nweeks ago. Mrs. Sohl is alleged to have admitted firing the fatal shot\nin the robbery which netted them $2.10. Barhorst leaves a wife and\ntwo children.\nMannish Ethel Stohl\nFired Murder Bullet\nShe Is Daughter of Policeman, Who Was One of 0f=\nfleers Assigned to Find Slayers\u2014Slain Bus\nDriver\u2019s Widow Happy at Arrest\nNewark, N. J., Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014\nMannish 20-year-old Ethel Stohl\nand her 17-year-old girl friend,\nGenevieve Owens, faced murder\ncharges today for slaying a bus\ndriver in a hold-up that netted them\n$2.10.\nThe girls confessed, police an\nnounced, that their brief criminal\ncareer resulted in the slaying of\nWilliam Barhorst, father of two\nyoung children, on the night of\nDecember 21 in Belleville, N. J.,\nnear Newark.\nMrs. Stohl, whose husband, Wil\nliam, 23, is serving and indetermin\nate term in the Annandale Re\nformatory for tampering with his\naged father\u2019s bank account, met\nMiss Owens in the County Reform\nschool. They formed a close friend\nship, and planned a series of hold\nups for \"pin money.\"\nDaughter of Policeman\nWhile they were being questioned,\nMrs. Stohl revealed that she was\nthe daughter of Prank Strouse. a\nNewark radio car policeman, who\nhad been among the patrolmen as\nsigned to search for the Barhorst\nslayers. Strouse collapsed when told\nof his daughter's confession.\nThe older girl amazed police by\nher mannish appearance and man\nner. She is tall, with close-cropped\nbobbed head, thin, firm lips and\nstern jaw. She wore a plaid lum\nber-jacket, and answered questions\nfor both herself and her young\nfriend, whom she affectionately\n(Continued on Page 4)\nPOPE PIUS SETS\nFEARS AT REST\nVatican City, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014'The\npope, setting at rest reports in the\nforeign press that he is suffering\nfrom a severe relapse, spent his\nmost active morning in weeks today.\nAfter he had celebrated mass in his\nprivate chapel, he was visited by\nProf. Arminto Milani, his physician.\nThen he granted audiences to Car\ndinal Pacelli, papal secretary of\nstate, and to a list of other high\nprelates in succession. Next came\nthe reception of 350 newlyweds.\nThe pope also received 300 mem\nbers of the Catholic Action and\nseveral hundred pilgrims. In a ten\nminute speech he remarked that\n\u201cthe holy see does not indulge in\npolitics, but only religion.\u201d\nMERRITT ROAD\nSTILL PROBED\nGovernor Cross Has Sug=\ngested Possible Ways\nto Get at All Facts\nBy JACK ZAIMAV\n(United Pres? Staff Correspondent)\nHartford, Conn., Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014\nThree possible avenues of investiga\ntion into rights-of-way purchases\nfor the 33-mile Merritt parkway\nwere suggested today by Governor\nWilbur L. Cross.\nWhich of the three the governor\nfavored, in event a criminal inves\ntigation of the state highway de\npartment purchases was decided\nupon, could not be learned, but it\nbecame increasingly evident he was\nveering away from the idea of a\ngrand pjury inquiry.\nIn daily press conferences with\nnewspapermen, the governor placed\ndecreasing emphasis on the grand\njury' proposal. He was represented\nby aids as feeling a grand jury in\nquiry might resolve itself into \"an\ninvestigation by one faction of the\nRepublican party into the other.\u201d\nBitter GOP Trend\nFairfield county Republicans now\nare engaged in a bitter internecine\nfeud between the old and new guard\nfactions.\nTo add to the doubt surrounding\nthe entire situation whereby alleg\nedly exhorbitant prices were paid\nby Highway Commissioner John A.\nMacdonald for rights-of-way, not\none of the five official groups inves\ntigating details of the transactions\nhave announced discovery of any\ncriminality in the deals.\nNevertheless, it was felt by com\npetent observers that the adminis\ntration may be forced into a crim\ninal investigation of circumstances\nsurrounding the land deals without\nany evidence that wrong-doing ex\nisted.\nIf an investigation were avoided,\n(Continued on Page 4)\nInforms President He\nVacates Supreme Court\nSeat On January 18\nBALANCING OF\nBUDGET FAILS\nPresident Presents Report\nto Congress\u2014Business\nRecession Caused It\nBy LYLE C. WILSON\n(L'nited Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington. Jan. 5.\u2014 <UP>\u2014Pres- j\nident Roosevelt reported to congress\ntoday that he had clamped brakes\non spending in an unsuccessful ef\nfort to balance budgets dislocated\nby business recession.\nMr. Roosevelt estimated the net\ndeficit for this (1938) fiscal year at\n$1,088,129,600 and for the 1939 fiscal\nyear at $949.606,000\u2014with the pros\npect that each actually will be\ngreater.\nThe president explained that re\ncession tremendously had reduced\nrevenue and prevented budget bal\nancing despite economies of $397,\n000.000 so far this year and $539,-\n000.000 next.\nPeace Time Record\nHe asked for a record breaking\npeace-time national defense appro\npriation of more than $1,000,000,000\nand another $1,000,000,000 for work\nrelief in the next fiscal year.\nHe said the national debt would\nrise to $38,528,200,000 by June 30.\n1939.\nIn attributing failure to balance\nthe budget to business recession.\nThe 1939 budget proposed reduc\ning spending by $539,000,000, which\nMr. Roosevelt regards as the most\nimportant fact in the bulky volume.\nThis is achieved largely by cutting\nitems dear to congress such as high\n1 ways, new public buildings, new re\nclamation and rivers and harbor\nprojects.\nMajor Economies\nDipping deeply into categories of\nexpenditure cherished by congress,\nI Mr. Roosevelt proposed major econ\ni omies, as follows:\n1. Cut the $280,000,000 highway\nfund in half and fix expenditure\nultimately at about $100,000,000 an\nnually. Request congress at this\nsession to cut appropriations ac\ncordingly; and urge state govern\nments to bring their highway budg\nets back to normal pre-depression\nlevels.\n2. Cut appropriations for new\nrivers and harbors projects from\n$81,200,000 to $60,000,000; provide\n(Continued on Page 4)\nSTATE FUNERAL\nFOR LORD PERLEY\nOttawa. Ont., Jan. 5.\u2014(UP)\u2014A\nstate funeral for the late Sir George\nPerley, American born Canadian\nstatesman who died yesterday will\nbe held here Friday.\nThe government will provide a\nRoyal Canadian Mounted Police\nescort for the semi-state funeral.\nMessages of sympathy were received\nby the family from all parts of Can\nada and the British empire, includ\ning condolences from King George,\nQueen Elizabeth and the Duke of\nConnaught, former governor-general\nof Canada.\nSir George had been prominent\nin Canadian political life since 1904.\nHe served as Canadian high com\nmissioner to London during the war\nyears, and was a member of the\nfirst imperial war cabinet.\nSir George was born in Lebanon.\nN. H., and received his education at\nSt. Paul\u2019s high school, Concorn, N.\nH., and Harvard university, where\nhe graduated in 1878. He later re\nceived an LL.D degree from Dart\nmouth.\nEx-Policeman Writes Play In Cell\nBy HARRY FERGUSON\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nNew York, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014Arthur\nChalmers walked a narrow cell in\nthe big red prison called the Tombs\ntoday and wondered whether the\nnext bend in the roadway of his life\nwould take him to the electric chair\nor to the gold and glory that go to\na successful playwright.\nHe is charged with murder, and\nin the weeks that he has waited for\ntrial he has been scribbling with\npen and ink on 18 sheets of paper\n\u2014scribbling the outline of a play\nthat will be called \u201cTaken From\nLife.\u201d It is an apt title, for Chal\nmers' material was taken from life,\ntaken from a true-story told him\nby an 18-year-old fellow prisoner.\nTomorrow Chamberlain Brown,\ntheatrical producer who took Chal\nmers\u2019 material and whipped it into\ndramatic form, begins casting \u201cTak\nen From Life\u201d. That leaves the\ndestiny of Chalmers in the hands\nof two juries. One is the jury that\nwill render soon a verdict of either\n\"guilty\u201d or \u201cnot guilty\u201d. The other\nis a jury composed of dramatic\ncritics, who, in about thre weeks,\nwill pronounce Judgment on \u201cTaken\nFrom Life\u201d.\nChalmers, a former policeman,\ntalked about his hopes and fear.'\nthrough the thick wire screen that\ndivides prisoners and visitors at the\nTombs.\n\u201cThe fellows down here are all\nthe time coming up to me and talk\ning,\u201d he said. \"They know I used\nto be a cop and they want to spill\na lot of stuff. An 18-year-oid kid\nwas one of them and the more he\ntalked to me the more I figured\nthat he had a swell story. I got\nsome ink and paper and started\nwriting it down. I changed all the\nnames, of course, and after working\nabout three weeks I\u2019d filled 18\nsheets of paper on both sides.\n\"I used to know Chamberlain\nBrown when I was on the police\nforce, so I mailed the stuff up to\nhim. I wondered if they changed\nit much.\u201d\nChalmers, former member of\ntroop B of the mounted police, was\narrested last August after the body\nof Miss Irma Louise Pradier had\nbeen found on the Harlem Speed\nway. Police said Chalmers confessed\nto the murder, but insisted that\ntjje shooting was an accident. His\nversion was that Miss Pradier\nthreatened him with a pistol when\nhe refused to go to California with\nher and that she was accidentally\nshot in the struggle that followed.\nAs he leaned against the wire\nscreen, Chalmers told why he\nmated \u201cTaken Rom Life\u201d to bo a\n\nhit.\n\u201cI got a wife and two kids,\u201d he\nsaid, \"and I haven't got a lawyer\nyet and I don't know when they\u2019re\ngoing to call my trial. I haven\u2019t\ngot any money and I sure could use\nsome. How much do you think I\nshould make off the play?\u201d\nHe was told that it depended on\nwhether the show was a hit,\nwhether motion picture companies\nwould be interested in buying the\nmovie rights and a hundred other\nfactors that make show business a\nhazardous undertaking. Chalmers\nnodded.\n\u201cWell, if I make some money out\nof it, I would be willing to give a\nlot of it to charity if X could get\nout of this place.\u201d\nThem he shuffled away from the\ncorridor, back to the cell where\nthere is nothing to do but wait and\nsee what the gods are arranging\nfor the next three months of his\nlife.\nBrown said \u201cTaken Prom Life,\u201d\nwas the story of a boy bom into\na criminal environment and the\nstruggles he had getting out of it.\n\u201cThere is a courtroom scene that\nis swell,\u201d the theatrical producer\nadded, \u201cand the whole thing has a\nvery unusual twist. This fellow\nChalmers really knows how to\nwrite.\u201d\nHas Served Sixteen Years as Member of\nHigh Tribunal; Follows Willis Van\nDe Vanter to Retirement\nBY RUSSELL TURNER\n{United Press Staff Correspondent)\nWashington, January 5. (UP) Supreme Court\nJustice George Sutherland today advised President Roose\nvelt that he will retire January 18 after 16 years as a mem\nber of the high tribunal. He follows Willis Van De Vanter\nas the second member of the court to take advantage of the\nretirement act which was nassed in the heat ot President\nRESIGNS OFFICE\nJUSTICE GEORGE SUTHERLAND\nTHIRTY FOUR ARE\nINJURED IN FIRE\nWere Attending Beano\nParty in Pawtucket;\nScenes of Terror\nPawtucket, R. I., Jan. 5.\u2014(UP'\u2014\nThirty-four persons were recover\ning today from injuries or smoke\ninhalation suffered when fire trap\nped more than 150 \u201cbeano\" players\nin a second-floor lodge hall last\nnight.\nFiremen carried nearly 100 to\nsafety over ladders, others jumped\nfrom windows and a few escaped\nthrough smoke-filled corridors be\nfore flames cut off their exit. Sev\neral of the injured suffered broken\nbones in falls.\nThe general-alarm firr, which\ncaused $25,000 damage, broke out\nin British-American hall in the\nbusiness district during the height\nof a Royal Arcanum \u201cbeano\" party.\nWhen smoke first seeped into the\nhall, the players mistook it for\nsteam from a radiator and by the\ntime they realized their danger, the\nstairway already was afire.\nWere Panic Stricken\nPanic-stricken men and women\nwere hanging from window sills\nwhen firemen arrived from head\nquarters only a block away. Lad\nders were raised hastily and within\n15 minutes, the building had been\ncleared.\nNine ambulances were pressed\ninto service to carry the injured to\nhospitals. Police and fire depart\nments broadcast the alarms for doc\ntors and nurses.\nTwo other parties were in pro\ngress in the building when the fire\nwas discovered. Seventy-five chil\ndren attending a British-American\nclub New Year\u2019s party in the base\nment and officers of the same club\nholding an installation in the first\nfloor hall escaped without difficulty.\nFAMILY BIBLE Is\nCAUSE OF SUIT\nWorcester, Mass., Jan. S\u2014(UP)\u2014\nA family Bible autographed by Rob\nert Shenpan, settler of New Haven,\nConn., was the center of a court\nfight involving the widow of a for\nmer speaker of the U. S. house of\nrepresentatives today. Counsel for\nthe estate of Miss Mary Hoar,\ndaughter of the late Senator George\nF. Hoar, has sued Mrs. Christine\nR. Hbar Gillett, widow of former\nSpeaker Frederick Gillett, for pos\nsession of the Bible.\nMrs. Gillett received the Bible 10\nyears ago as executrix of the will of\nher first husband, the late U. S.\nRepresentative Rockwood Hoar,\nwilled the Bible to her cousin, Roger\nbrother of Miss Hoar. Miss Hoar\nSherman Warner of Boston. Coun\nsel for Mrs. Gillett contends the suit\nis outlawed by the statute of lim\nitations.\nAWAITS HIS MOTHER\nNew York. Jan. 5.\u2014(UP).\u2014Allen\nLudbook, IS, was at the Children's\nsociety today awaiting the arrival\nof his mother from Pittsfield, Mass.\nHe hitchhiked here and asked police\nfor advice on how to get back. They\nsent him to the shelter and notified\nMrs. Mary Uudbook*\nRoosevelt's unsuccessful attempt to\nenlarge the court. The act permits\nretirement of Justices after they\nreach the age of 75 at full salary\nof $20,000 annually. Sutherland, who\nis 76 and one of the three staunch\nconservative jurists left on the high\nbench, wrote President Roosevelt:\n\u201cX hereby retire from regular ac\ntive service on the bench, this re\ntirement to be effective on and after\nTuesday, the 18th dav of January,\n1938.\"\nGives His Reason\nAdvanced age and a feeling that\nhe no longer could continue the\npace required of Supreme Court\njustices were advanced by his friends\nand associates as Sutherland\u2019s rea\nson for retirement.\nSutherland\u2019s departure from the\nbench will permit President Roose\nvelt to name his second nominee for\nmembership on the high bench. Af\nter four years during which he had\nno appointments to the court. Mr.\nRoosevelt named as his first choice\nJustice Hugo L. Black to suceed Van\nDe Vanter.\nSutherland's retirement also\nstrengthens the position of the so\ncalled \"liberal\u201d majority of the\ncourt, composed of Justices Charles\nEvans Hughes, Benjamin N. Car\ndozo, Harlan P. Stone, Louis D.\nBrandeis and Black.\nTwo Conservatives Left\nIt reduces the one-time conserva\ntive majority now the minority\nI \u2014to but two members, Justices\nPierce Butler and James C. McRey\n(Continued on Page 8)\njapaYgrabbing\nRADIO SERVICE\nSerious Crisis Is Expected\nIf United States and\nBritain Objects\nBT EDWARD W. BEATTIE\n(United Press Staff Correspondent)\nShanghai, Jan 5\u2014A new and\nserious clash between Japanese and\nforeign interests was threatened to\nday as Shanghai municipal author\nities referred to the United States\nand British governments a Japanese\ndemand for virtual control of the\ninternational settlement. Foreseeing\na clash of interests, the Shanghai\nmunicipal government referred the\nJapanese demands to the United\nStates and Great Britain through\nthe American and British consul\nates general here. Settlement auth\norities planned to make no reply to\nthe Japanese demands until they\nhad received specific reaction from\nWashington and London.\nSeeks Domination\nVigorously pressing an apparent\ncampaign for domination of the for-\neign settlement, with its gigantic\nAmerican, British and other foreign\ninterests, the Japanese today took\nover operation of all radio stations\nand installed Japanese censors who\nwill be ready at a moment\u2019s notice\nto exert control over all messages\nincluding foreign ones.\nThis would mean that the Japa\nnese, operating in the International\nSettlement, would censor American\nand other foreign newspaper dis\n(Continued on Page 4)\n|treasury balance\nWashington, Jan. 5\u2014(UP)\u2014Gov\u00ab\nernment expenses and receipts for\nthe current fiscal year through Jan.\n3rd, compared with a year ago:\nThis Year Expenses Last Yeav\n$3,909,020,201.09 $3,600,329,868.85\nReceipts\n$3,196,418,447.02 $2,198,281,455.71\nDeflct\n$712,601,754,07 $1,402,048,413.05\nch Ttnlanon\n*2,956,036,920.29 S1,903,683,77S.:6\n/rtcsiamn us\npmnr omce'\nTHKTf\nLK